3.title: Elf ears
3.description: This is the result of the tutorial video on MakeTarget, and is uploaded here mainly as an illustration. The target makes the ears long and pointy, traditional elf style.

4.title: Basic female
4.description: This is a test model where I just basically moved the gender slider. It's here just so the table isn't empty, and I'll delete it once there are better contributions in the repository.

10.title: Nose piercing
10.description: Just a very basic nose piercing to test uploading of clothes.

11.title: Combat boots
11.description: My quick and dirty adaptation of a CC0 model from blendswap http://www.blendswap.com/blends/view/15722 to MakeClothes. Looks decent as is, but probably could benefit from additional polish and texturing, maybe even several different textures. Corresponding forum thread: http://www.makehumancommunity.org/forum/viewtopic.php?f=4&t=11332

12.title: Celtic Summer Skirt and Bodice
12.description: A traditional Celtic Summer Skirt and Bodice, also with a Jewelled Headress in the Wavefront object.  This outfit is designed to work with the Female Muscular Topology, set for slightly above average height.

13.title: Celtic Jewelled Headdress
13.description: A Celtic Jewelled Headdress, designed as an accessory to the Celtic Summer Skirt and Bodice.  The figure-eight ribbon bindings are quite a high poly count!

15.title: Minoan Hairdo One
15.description: The first in a series of Minoan and Ancient Greek hair styles.  This one is inspired by a 4,000-year-old mosaic found in Crete.  The material is tinted blue, to make it easier to work with on the screen.  I've updated the UV map, and added a new diffuse texture of one-pixel-wide lines. This wig will work on any standard Makehuman female.

16.title: Body Armor Shoulder Holster
16.description: A 'casual combat' outfit for an athletic female. It wasn't made to be pretty!  The pants are tight, but the boots and jacket are heavy.  There is a bullet-proof vest with a large shoulder holster rig.  The holster was designed to hold a Lady Glock Model 17, but you can change that in the mesh.  The jacket is purposely opened on the left side so that you can pose this character in actions such as drawing and firing. The material is 'Gun Metal Blue'.  The diffuse texture map is an Apophysis fractal . I'm thinking this character would use some sort of 'chameleon' armor.

18.title: Renaissance Oval Veil and Wimple
18.description: A Renaissance (or Celtic) oval veil and wimple, to finish the my 'Celtic Summer' design.  The texture is an Apophysis fracture that should look like bluish silk.  This mesh should work for any female model.

19.title: Gina Carano Action Figure
19.description: What I like best about the new body sliders is how realistic they are.  This is the standard female model, with above average Height and Weight, but full Muscularity and especially Full Proportion.  Also my favourite Hair Mesh, the new braid.  This model is designed for action animations.

20.title: Beach Poncho (Rain Slicker)
20.description:
A very simple poncho design. If you want added details, then contact me.  I am designing templates for other 3d artists at this point. 
I had to use a render rather than a screen shot because my Gina Carano model was too much for this garment.  Should work well with less heroic physiques!

21.title: Crude Bra
21.description:
The crude series of clothes are intended as starting points for further development. They are mostly low-poly and intended for subdivision (and may therefore look a bit clunky inside MakeHuman). Each piece comes with a plain diffuse texture where the faces have been painted plain white.

If you modify or texture paint one of the pieces in this series and want to share, just upload it again here as if you were the original author of it.

If you modify or texture paint one of the pieces in this series and want to share, just upload it again here as if you were the original author of it.

33.title: Pink Fuzzy Bathrobe with Pink Clogs
33.description:
Well, you know how it is. I started out to make a 'Long Rider' coat with boots, but ended up with a 'Pink Fuzzy Bathrobe with Pink Clogs'.
That's why the name change.  But, your character can always fantasize about wearing a 'Long Rider' coat.  This outfit should work for all female body types.

34.title: Celtic Princess One
34.description: A formal Celtic gown, with puffed shoulders, and 'tulip' style sleeves.  I'm going to add a jewelled belt, and chains around the shoulders and elbows (and jewelled slippers)  , but I've discovered that sort of 'bling' needs to be done separately, or the mesh deformations become too severe.  This mesh should work on any female.

35.title: Minoan Slave One
35.description: A very simple garment, that features 'real' chain bracelets and a chain necklace. If anyone is interested, I'll post a tutorial on it. Basically, in Blender one creates a torus with an empty modifier (to offset the next link, and to control its rotation), then  adds a Bezier circle to the torus, and sets the array to 24 items. Voila!  This model should work on any human.

36.title: Military Poncho (Hood Up)
36.description: A military poncho with the hood up. Should work for any Makehuman model. The big trick in designing this one so that it poses well is to create the outer edges first, and then work inward, draping as you go.

37.title: Cargo Pants
37.description: A pair of cargo pants to complement the military poncho and combat boots. Should work on all Makehuman models.

38.title: Anus_Deep
38.description:
creates a deepness in anus but ATTENTION you need to make it nice the other two targets : Anus small width and Anus small length
Best results with Proxy Topology Adult Female Genetialia.

39.title: Anus small Width
39.description: creates a deepness in anus but ATTENTION you need to make it nice the other two targets : Anus deep and Anus length Best results with Proxy Topology Adult Female Genetialia.

40.title: Anus Small Length
40.description: creates a deepness in anus but ATTENTION you need to make it nice the other two targets : Anus deep and Anus small Width. Best results with Proxy Topology Adult Female Genetialia.

41.title: Vulva Narrow (for Adult Female Genetialia)
41.description: It only makes sense with Adult Female Genetialia. It deforms the standard mesh to reduce the stretching of the vulva that the two labia get more together.

42.title: Vulva Short (for Adult Female Genetialia)
42.description: It only makes sense with Adult Female Genetialia. It deforms the standard mesh to reduce the length of the vulva.

43.title: Vulva Deep Top (for Adult Female Genetialia)
43.description: It only makes sense with Adult Female Genetialia. It deforms the standard mesh to bring the inner range in the top region deeper inside the vulva.

44.title: Vulva Deep Middle (for Adult Female Genetialia)
44.description: It only makes sense with Adult Female Genetialia. It deforms the standard mesh to bring the inner range in the middle region deeper inside the vulva.

45.title: Vulva Deep Low (for Adult Female Genetialia)
45.description: It only makes sense with Adult Female Genetialia. It deforms the standard mesh to bring the inner range in the lower region deeper inside the vulva.

46.title: Slave Girl Metal Bra
46.description: Because you know you want one!  Here is a Slave Girl Metal Bra, using a simple triad Celtic knot.  This design should not cause any copyright problems.  Should work with any adult female.

47.title: Slave outfit
47.description: I've made a slave gown based on "Minoan Slave One" work by brkurt: http://www.makehumancommunity.org/clothes/minoan_slave_one.html I've basically taken his object and changed it over a bit, subdivided, solidified and ran cloth simulation on it. I've also made a texture (that's my first experience in texturing so don't go too hard on me). In texturing I've used some of publicly available cloth textures, but I think I've cannibalized them enough that it doesn't matter. Due to the known limitation of MakeClothes that allows only one material per clothing, the collar and bracers would need to be separate items. Maybe I'll make those too if I have time.

48.title: Victoria's Celtic Secret One
48.description: Erin Go Bragh! Indeed. Here is a halter top created from the Lindisfarne celtic knot. This mesh is going to go through a lot of revisions. Should work for any adult female model.

50.title: Spartan Warrior Woman
50.description: Not really sure if Spartan women went to war, and I doubt that they wore boiled-leather armor, but it looks great. I'll be adding details as I go.  Should work for any adult female.

51.title: Spartan Warrior Cape
51.description: A short (knee-length) cape that goes over the hair mesh quite nicely. To be used with the Spartan Warrior Woman armor. Should work for all adult females.

52.title: Spartan Warrior Greves
52.description: The Spartan Warrior outfit, one accessory at a time. You will have to adjust these greves to your model manually, as I found the difference between the base mesh and the muscular topology are quite severe.

53.title: Spartan Gaunlet & Gloves
53.description: A simple gauntlet-and-glove mesh set (need buckles and insignia).  Should work for any adult Makehuman model

55.title: Slave collar  Chain
55.description:
As promised, I've tried to make a chain collar for slave outfit. I've also tried to make an actual one-piece collar, but it appears as though everything around the neck of MH model gets deformed pretty bad. I have no idea as to how to fight this. It looks a bit better with chain collar, but it's still far from perfect. I've shown it on the base MH model, on actual models it only gets worse. For the texture I used a free one from http://naldzgraphics.net/textures/free-seamless-metal-textures/ It appears to be unburdened. Anyway, it will work just as well with any metal texture.

UPD 02/09/2015: I have remade the collar with special vertex group so that it won't be deformed quite so badly. It works much better now, but there still may be problems with particularly large characters or ones with really thick neck.

56.title: Sari One
56.description: A very simple template for a three-piece sari of skirt, halter and sash. (I'll put the proper Indian names in later). I've twisted the sash so that it will curve around the body.

58.title: Very low poly
58.description: This is a proxy with a very low number of faces (408). Specifically, it does not have mesh geometry for inside mouth, fingers or toes. It does work with existing MakeHuman skins to the extent of the main body, but hands and feet do not fit (they have been placed on subsections of the hand/feet areas of the skin textures. The proxy should deform reasonably well using existing rigs.

59.title: Hermitess One
59.description: No Kung Fu movie is complete without a fighting Hermitess, so here you go.  You will have to adjust the belt and sleeves, but the hood came through beautifully (it is designed to cover the Braid).  Should work for any adult female model.

60.title: Genie One
60.description: A flying, fighting girl djinn for y'all.  Or harem slave, if you prefer.  I've made the slippers and hair part of the outfit this time. I'll add veil and embroidery later, but this should be useful for some folks right now. Should work for any adult female.

62.title: Annotated skin
62.description: This is a demonstration skin which marks locations of various body areas and seams. Connection points are labeled with letters and colors. Outside the skin texture as such, there are explanatory labels. The XCF file has the labels on separate layers.

63.title: Gi One
63.description: A simple martial arts gi.  If you want a detailed design for your particular dojo/discipline, just contact me. Should work for any adult female.  A note to designers: there are four surfaces that cannot be allowed to intersect, and in order to make the belt work, I had to solidify it.

64.title: Big Desert Poncho
64.description: A template (only!) for a full desert poncho.  If you want details added, contact me.  Also, you will need to create vertex groups that allow the cloth to move with the arms or legs separately.  In Blender, you can do this by automatically rigging when you export from Makehuman.  Should work for any adult female.

65.title: nostrils flat
65.description: Not sure what to call this, but I couldn't seem to make the nose do this without making a custom slider for it.

67.title: Slave collar  full metal
67.description:
After the comment by ThimasL in http://www.makehumancommunity.org/forum/viewtopic.php?f=3&t=12101 I've learned about the way to make rigid things in MH by creating custom vertex groups. As such, I've made another attempt to make a full metal slave collar and after fiddling with vertex groups a lot that's what I came up with. It's still far from perfect, but it looks MUCH better that what would otherwise happen. I'll probably update the chain one (http://www.makehumancommunity.org/clothes/slave_collar.html ) later using this knowledge.

UPD 02/09/2015: This asset seems to behave weird when used on large characters or ones with particularly thick necks.

70.title: Female Fingernails
70.description:
Not really clothing, but additional geometry like eyebrows. Use subdivision modifier in Blender. Important: Use same subdivision level on body and fingernails. Works with base mesh, female generic, female muscle 13442 and adult female genitalia. Normal map needs improvement.

Update 22.08.2015: Material file updated. Fingernails were too shiny.

71.title: Braided Pig Tails
71.description: A simple set of braided pig tails.  I have designed them to be detachable (in Blender, use the Rip command [ctrl + v]) so that you can place them anywhere you want on the scalp. Should work for any adult female, and probably for little girls too.

72.title: Helen Of Troy
72.description: The braids that took a thousand hours!  This one is very experimental--it doesn't look good in the Makehuman GUI, but looks great as a Collada export.  The idea here was to accurately recreate one of the very complex hairstyles of the ancient Greek world.  The bangs are curled upward, there are scalplocks with rings, and the top of the head has eight braids, so that the hair looks very thick. Should work for any adult female. Check out the video at: https://youtu.be/FTkuwRQdxT8

73.title: scarf
73.description: I applied cloth simulation to a torus and that's it. I have no idea what I'm doing, feel free to modify it.

74.title: Brunhilde (Nibelungenlied)
74.description: A sculpted hairpiece based on an old painting of Brunhilde. For you Wagnerian types. It clears the body quite well, so it should move well.  Best to use on an adult female model.  The diffuse texture map is made up of 1 pixel lines of color, so if you want to make the hair more photo-realistic, just adjust the UV map.

75.title: Mermaid (Seaweed Hair and Dolphin Tail)
75.description:
A rough sketch, but use-able none the less.  Here is your basic mermaid costume.  Should work for any female. 
Check out the video at: https://youtu.be/FTkuwRQdxT8

76.title: Mermaid One
76.description: A very simple color inversion of a light-skinned young human female, which creates a nice blue-green color. Meant for aliens or mermaids.

77.title: Ronda Rousey Blonde Corn Rows
77.description: The hairstyle of choice for female MMA fighters.  You can create your own corn row texture maps, this one works for me.

78.title: Newsboy cap
78.description:
A simple little hat. All you get for the a texture is the exported UV map, though. It also tends to clip through the hair models.

edit: added a texture made using this procedural fabric shader: http://www.blendswap.com/blends/view/76372

79.title: Dutch Baby Bonnet
79.description: A simple baby bonnet with a string tie. The hair is already fitted under the bonnet. Should work for any model, but I intended it for babies.

80.title: Wrestling suit
80.description:
I made a rather simple model for wrestling tights that are used in classical/graeco-roman/freestyle wrestling. It is a rather simple piece of clothing mostly out of a part of "tights" helper with some minute modifications. As such, I expect it to work in any MH model (but I only tested them for male characters, can't be sure how it interacts with boobs!)
The textures are very simple (I made them mostly in KolourPaint) and also rather choppy, cause I suck at this. If anyone can make better textures for this, please let me know so that I'll be able to update them!

Upd 2016/01/13: As I'm getting slightly better with UV-maps and texturing, I've decided to update this asset with a better mapped sample. It is still far from perfect, but already better and easier to work with.

82.title: Luchador mask
82.description: The other day I've got a weird idea to make a full-face mask from Mexican Lucha libre for MH. This design is very simple, it's basically Joel's "Crude ski mask" http://www.makehumancommunity.org/clothes/crude_ski_mask.html with small modifications and subdivision. The texture, as before, I've made in KolourPaint, it's as simple as it gets. I've done a bit of research and found out there are hundreds of designs for masks in this sport, pretty much each wrestler has their own design and for them the mask is an important way to express their individuality and almost a sacred symbol. Of all possible designs I've chosen one of the simplest, colloquially known as "monkey face".

83.title: Dragon Bodysuit Female White
83.description:
This is the Dragon Bodysuit for the white female, 

Included is a skin tattoo with permanent make-up on eyebrows, eyelids and lips for light tanned females. The cosmetics for eyebrows and lids were taken from the young_caucasian_female_special_suit texture and the base skin for the tattoo was taken from the young_lightskinned_female_diffuse3.png, so there was no editing necessary to match the skin tone

The texture of real lips was slightly different than the dark female dragon bodysuit and it was taken here:
https://bugsbeautyblogdotcom.files.wordpress.com/2010/12/dsc_0450.jpg 

Other textures as follows: (Credit where credit is due)
Dragon on body and face: 
http://kuzzie-013.deviantart.com/art/Dragon-Tattoo-108471312 

Bat wings with skeleton on neck:
http://pix-hd.com/cat+wings+costume

Chinese symbol (dragon) at the back of the neck:
http://www.taiwanese-secrets.com/image-files/475x320xchinese-dragon-symbol.001.jpg.pagespeed.ic.9j6bCGWvUz.jpg

Fairy wings on the dcollet:
http://purrplecatt.deviantart.com/art/Fairy-Wings-65821439

Yin & Yang symbol with hearts:
http://yinyangmother.com/nothing-is-ever-black-and-white/

Rose on upper chest:
http://www.voilamontatouage.com/tatouages-fleurs/4596-tatouage-tribal-de-rose-2.html

Rose on outer chest:
https://www.pinterest.com/explore/tribal-rose-tattoos/

Rose on upper back:
http://www.freetattoodesigns.org/images/tattoo-gallery/barbed-wire-tattoo.jpg

Wings at the back of the shoulders:
http://fc09.deviantart.net/fs32/f/2008/198/a/c/wings_by_contiamirian.png

Japanese Koi on the upper legs:
http://griffon2745.deviantart.com/art/Koi-Fish-Tattoo-Design-2-378476282


Installation instruction for newbies:
To install it into the Makehuman skins library, right-click on each file here (.mhmat and .thumb) and choose Save As..., create a new folder "dragon_female_white" under the main program folder: Makehuman 1.x.x/data/skins/dragon_female_white and download the .mhmat and the .thumb file to it. Then go to Makehuman 1.x.x/data/skins/textures and download the .png (diffuse texture) file to it.
Execute Makehuman and navigate to Materials, choose "Dragon female white" and apply it to your avatar.


Enjoy!

Included is a complete skin tattoo with permanent make-up on eyebrows, eyelids and lips for dark tanned females. The perfect cosmetics for eyebrows and lids was taken from the young_caucasian_female_special_suit texture and edited to fit the dark skin.

95.title: MMA/Fighting gloves
95.description: I've made a pair of gloves that are used in MMA and other combat sports for protecting the athlete's hands. It is also the first time I used a new and revolutionary method of creating textures by splitting the object and then texture painting each of its parts separately. The result, dare I say, doesn't look that horrible! I've also used a render from MakeClothes base human as a preview rather than an actual model, this is just because it seemed easier that way.

130.title: Topboots one
130.description:
Here's an object I tried to "quadrungulate" by shrinkwrapping a square mesh onto a public domain non-quad model. It kinda works, but the fit is a bit imperfect. The mesh itself is a mess, especially at the lower part of the boot. I couldn't quite understand what's going on there.
NB: when exporting as MHX2 causes a few NaN points that prevent the model from being imported. I just opened the .mhx2 file in vim and replaced all occurrences of nan with 0 and then it worked.

So, let me know what you guys think if this is a viable way to do quad clothes, because all the other things I tried didn't work at all. This one at least "kinda" works.

199.title: Mermaid
199.description:
There's a very useful tutorial series on youtube about rigging the mermaid tail, beginning with this:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pGloKeDgH4k

                             In short: you will want to rig the tail to only one leg. So you have to clear the weightings from the other leg and give it to the first one.

When you decide to create a well-fed mermaid, you will notice that the midline-vertices behave strangely. You can easily bring them back to their y-position in edit mode. No need to get frustrated ;) Use the diffuse texture for color and transparency. Use the normal map as usual. Use the spec map for spec color and spec intensity.

200.title: Four Strand Braid

205.title: Peeptoe boot
205.description: If you need another skin tone, you could stencil the needed texture from one of the MH skins, using e.g. gimp. That's why i kept the UV location of the footmesh at the original MakeHuman-UV location.  To prevent strange bendings at the heel, you probably will need to erase the weighting for the bones DEF-shin-03 L and R at the heel area (make them visible by activating the last bonelayer's visibility). It should even be possible to weight paint the toes in order to use the toe helper bones to bend them.

219.title: Elven girl
219.description:
So here I post my model of an Elven girl. The assets used are:

*Adult Female topology by Manuel Bastioni http://www.makehumancommunity.org/proxy/adult_female_genitalia_by_manuel_bastioni.html

*Elf ears by Joel Palmius http://www.makehumancommunity.org/target/elf_ears.html

*Vulva narrow target by frankaye http://www.makehumancommunity.org/target/vulva_narrow_for_adult_female_genetialia.html

*Bow tie hair by grinsegold http://www.makehumancommunity.org/clothes/wig_female_bow_tie.html

*And Elven skin by yours truly :) http://www.makehumancommunity.org/skin/elven_skin.html

The background image is just one of the first hits in google for keyword "waterfall": https://wallpaperscraft.com/image/waterfall_stream_rocks_landscape_86093_3840x2400.jpg

I deliberately didn't put any clothes on her, I think she doesn't need them. And if you think she looks too young for this shizz, think again. Those damn treehuggers live for centuries, never really grow and never really get old. This one might have been around during Napoleonic wars, watching the battle of Austerlitz from the treetops of Moravian forests :)

247.description: A goth/steampunk jacket for average female

248.title: Elf Warrior
248.description:
Elf Warrior clothes made for average male..   I have added an Anisotropic texture for the Metal parts under optional displacement texture as the realistic metal look can only be achieved in blender if you select the vertices in edit mode and set that material to anisotropic then plug in the anisotropic texture as color.  if you dont do this then you will have matte white texture.

EDIT: I Re-exported this and all seems to be working now.

249.title: N'Varr boot
249.description: Here I upload new boots. The mesh they're based on I've found in the internet, it was called N'varr boots. It was associated with some character, but in the time it took me to make them MH-ready I've forgot what character it was or even which fandom it comes from. Probably Star Wars something, but won't bet on it. Nevertheless, despite not knowing what kind of creature wears this kind of boots, they look decent so I think why to share them? Known issues: may look bat shit weird in MH, but after export everything's alright. Subdivision modifier recommended after importing. I also upload the mask in specular texture slot, it can be used as an AO texture or as basis for creating new diffuse textures more easily.

250.title: Chain Mail Headdress One
250.description: Strictly a template, for learning to animate a screen mesh.  This one will only work with a high-power workstation!  Should work for any adult female.

251.title: Elf Warrior Leg outfit
251.description: Part of the Elf Warrior outfit i designed - this being for the legs.  As with the Elf Warrior jacket, i include here an Anisotropic material, the difuse material is automatically applied, but that is only for the brown fabric sections on the legs, for the rest  - in blender you need to choose the vertices that will be metal in edit mode and then set that material to Anisotropic then plug the texture provided into the color. this is the only way to get a realistic metal material -  If you do not do this then the metal will appear matte white.

252.title: Chain Mail Belt One
252.description: This one is tricky!  If you don't get the sequence right, vertices will have more than 8 poles, and therefore won't compile in MakeClothes.  Also, just this is a very data-intensive mesh, so I'm going to create the belt buckle (clasp?) separately.  Finally, this mesh won't load properly into my present unstable version of Makehuman, but the wavefront object imports and exports into several versions of Blender without a problem.

253.title: Anime hair test
253.description: After I saw the technique of making anime-style haircuts out of individual blades, I tried it and then thought I'm done with it. Nevertheless, I continued to experiment and tested it quite a bit, until I finally came up with something that looked almost half-decent. The problems I mentioned in the thread  too many overlap, overcomplicated mesh etc are still there, but I thought might as well share what I have got. Who knows, maybe somebody will use it for something, or maybe it will give somebody new ideas. There's still not a lot of usable hair in MH repository, so I guess every little bit helps

294.title: [LINGERIE] Stockings Black Fishnet Small
294.description: <<Tip>>: the stockings come in 6 different variations. For a better overview you can make it changeable under the Material Tab instead of Clothes. Create therefore just one folder under ../v1/data/clothes/, name it for example stockings_fishnet and copy all files of one variation into it. Take for example stockings_fishnet_large as the main files. Rename them to stockings_fishnet and edit the .mhclo file to match the new names. E.g. rename stockings_fishnet_large.obj to stockings_fishnet.obj, rename stockings_fishnet_large.mhmat to stockings_fishnet.mhmat etc. Change the new names within the .mhclo files too. [IMPORTANT: DO NOT RENAME THE .PNG FILE, unless you're willing to edit its name within the .mhmat file too] Create then a subfolder named materials and within it create 5 additional subfolders, named after your choice. For example: stockings_fishnet_medium, stockings_fishnet_small etc. Now copy only three files of each version, the .mhmat, the .thumb and the .png into the appropriate subfolder. For example copy stockings_fishnet_medium.mhmat, stockings_fishnet_medium.thumb and stockings_fishnet_medium.png into the stockings_fishnet_medium subfolder, delete the .mhclo and the .obj file. And now the important part, rename the .mhmat and the .thumb file to match the name in the main folder, so that the main .mhclo file could find it, in this case rename it to stockings_fishnet.mhmat and stockings_fishnet.thumb, again, leave the .png file (unless you're willing to edit it's name within the .mhmat file). Do the same procedure with all 5 subfolders and voila your 6 different stockings appear properly under the Material Tab as Stockings fishnet.<</Tip>>

386.title: F Dress 04
386.description:
Tags: Female, Elegant.
Not as much folds on this one as I thought of comfortable spandex like fabric.
I made the buckle a hard body but in some cases it will loose its rectangular geometry.
The diffuse texture and specular map looks the same but they are not. The specular map is specially made for Blender Cycles and should be set to "Non-Color Data".

In Blender Cycles you can also use the specular map to get different glossy roughness between the fabric and the metal parts. Add a "math"-node and set it to "Multiply" and connect the color output of the specular map into the "math"-node upper slot and set the value to eg 24, then add a "Invert"-node and connect the "Math"-node to the color input of the "Invert-node" and the "Invert"-node output to the glossy roughness input.

The preview is how the dress should look in Blender Cycles after above settings.
Updated 2017-07-15 Made new vertex binding to get some better deformations on the skirt and the belt buckle.

387.title: String 4
387.description: String 4 should be used with the Bandeau bra. It also should fit under the cocktaildress. A white texture will be added in the material section.

390.title: M Suit 01
390.description:
Tags: Male, Elegant.
Tailored suit, but the shirt and tie are fake. The normal map do most of the other details. I made the buttons three vertex hard body but I could't get them to work in all situations without them loosing their shape and location. If the buttons are important you could get them from the OBJ-file and place them manually.

The textures is primary made for subsurf level 2 in Blender.
If you use Blender try the Solidify modifier with "Fill Rim" and "Only Rim" to give the fabric some thickness.

For fast specular setup in Blender Cycles, set the specular map to "Non-Color Data", connect the color output to the upper value input of a "Math"-node, set it to "Power" and the value to about 5, and then use the output of the "Math"-node as mixfactor between Diffuse BSDF/Glossy BSDF shader.

The tie print is from Maialisa on pixabay.com, CC0 Public Domain.

391.title: Tight jeans (female)

The textures can also be used for the short jeans.

Edit: A normal-map is added. Best way to use the material in Blender: duplicate it and use a less glossy version for the fabric (e.g. connect input color of glossy shader to output of diffuse texture, you can also delete the fresnel and use a fixed value instead), use the glossy version for the buttons (set roughness of glossy shader to a low value). 



Change:  I added the "delete_verts" to the end of the .mhclo file. If you do not want them, simply throw these lines away.

Since short jeans and tight jeans are using exactly the same textures you can also edit the .mhmat file, so that you only have to load it one time.

This piece is on the back of the skull and should be hidden or removed after import into Blender.

You also have to edit the small tie in front after importing the dress into blender, when you use a female with a bigger cup-size. The tie becomes smaller when the breast size increases, but the geometry is not changed. So by selecting all vertices of the tie in Blender it is simple to make modifications.

407.description: This is the material I created first for the babydoll simply by using a checkerboard pattern instead of the pattern and a darker transparent layer. It works fine with Makehuman, in Blender it becomes more or less invisible.

409.title: Asymmetric Tunic and Sash
409.description:
A sleeveless woman's tunic with asymmetric seams and hem, with a sash around the hips. Fitted on the female base human. The diffuse texture is derived from GIMP's built-in Wildflowers pattern and one of my really old procedural textures where I was attempting to make wood and not succeeding (makes pretty good stripes, though). The normal and specular maps come from a desaturated fabric photo and an old pattern where I literally modelled thread with lots and lots of tiny cylinders. (A grayscale bump map was baked first, then I used that to bake normals.) Most skirts/pants/underwear should fit underneath with no or minor clipping, and there's enough mesh density in the chest area to fit most, ahem, cup sizes.

Known Issues
- Minor clipping or odd deformations occur in front of the armpits when the shoulders are rolled (you can see it on the Benchmark or other extreme arm poses). For now it's easy enough to hot-fix in Blender, until I figure out which helper verts are the guilty party.

Plans
- Add a tie for the sash. This might be better done as a separate accessory.

As always you have to rework the breast region after you imported it in Blender, when your character has big cupsizes, usually by smoothing it.  In reality you can buy the dress in 6 different colors. I only add the white material. As a material I tried a combination of normal-map and diffuse-texture which works in MH itself. So I took the leather litsphere. When you export it to blender the litsphere does not matter, because the materials and textures are added as always.Please read the small tutorial in the forum for other colors. Delete-Vertex group is used now.

415.title: Pith Helmet
415.description:
A classic jungle explorer pith helmet. Fitted on the neutral base human. The cap area is actually separate from the brim, with the cords hiding the empty space. This let me add more loops to the cap to make the seams, while not having to add unneeded loops to the brim just to match topology. It fits over short hairstyles without issue, but most long hair will clip through. You can hot-fix this in Blender with shape keys and/or a Mask modifier.

Known Issues -
Scales a little unevenly. (You can see some minor squash and stretch when moving the Age slider.) I tried several 3-vertex combos on the Hair helper for the rigid fit method, and this is the best result of the bunch.

You also should make the whole material a little bit more shiny, when you use the normal map. An example of the cycles shader setup is placed in the forum.

It was not simple to do it, because of only quads and the fitting of the vertex-groups to the character. I hope I've done it correctly. For all of those you, who like to have the blend file with more functionality I will also upload the file including a small tutorial. For the materials I added a diffuse-texture and a setup with backface-culling off and transparency on, so that MH will display something (and will not delete the hair when you look through the glasses).

428.title: Crude sword
428.description: An item intended to demonstrate non-deforming vertex groups. Here the entire sword has been assigned to a vertex group called "*sword" (note the asterisk). Then, on the human, exactly three vertices on the edges of the palm of the hand holding the sword have been assigned to "*sword". This is intended to demo how to create rigid groups which scales linearly with the size of the toon (in this case the distance between the three vertices in the palm) rather than deform in strange ways.

429.title: brazilian bikini (bra)

A few elements of the bra are placed on special vertex-groups, so that these are not distorted, but it is possible that these elements look like loose geometry. After importings these elements to blender change the material of spheres, rings and end sleeves to brass. The cylinder is a plastic material.
Delete-groups are used. No normal map appended so far.

430.title: brazilian bikini (slip)

433.title: Short-Tail Camo Tee
433.description:
A casual shirt with the tail not quite reaching the hips, fully modeled seams and a camouflage pattern. Fitted on the female base human. (Works okay for males, too, albeit with a "shrunk in the wash" look.) The camo was created with procedural textures, multiplied down with a light AO map, and then baked to an image. The specular map emphasizes self-shadowing in the seams. The normal map simulates individual stitches to produce a fabric-like sheen. (The effect is more like satin than cotton, but close enough.) The chest area readily adapts to standard breast targets, though minor clipping can occur with extreme combinations.

Known Issues -
A bit of ugly deformation in the armpits. Can be hot-fixed in Blender with Subsurf and Corrective Smooth modifiers.

As a material I tried a combination of normal-map and diffuse-texture which works in MH itself. So I took the leather litsphere. When you export it to blender the litsphere does not matter, because the materials and textures are added as always. I added a picture in the forum (tutorials/coloring white texture...) how you change the material in Blender cycles to display every color you want and also how to change the details. The shirt uses the delete-group. All 5 buttons of the shirt resize geometrically! Scale down the 4th button, when you use bigger cup-sizes in Blender. Select all buttons in Blender and attach a new more shiny material (e.g. put a math-node (+ 0.5, clamp) between fresnel and mix-shader).

497.title: Cmu Default Hybrid Rig
497.description:
INTRODUCTION:

The purpose of this rig is to combine the simplicity and easy of motion capture usability through "MakeWalk" plugin for Blender of the "CMU mb" Rig while having the bone complexity for facial and hand movements of the "Default" Rig, both of which come with Makehuman 1.1.0 . Many of the facial bones that you see on the "Default" rig are missing purposefully because the Mhx2 export format has visemes facial mesh functionality that makes the extra bones a bit redundant. This rig was designed to be ideal for previsualization use in Blender imported from Makehuman in the Mhx2 format. This rig utilizing the best aspects of both rigs and Mhx2 visemes to retain simplicity for better real-time viewport function while maximizing robustness (example: Character angrily holding a gun and walking(thru mocap) while speaking a monologue).                                         

KNOWN ISSUES:

This guide is specifically for Blender (tested 2.78) once the makehuman model has been imported in the Mhx2 format.
The rig looks perfectly in terms of connections and bones but there are weight paint issues on all hand and face rig elements. Weight paint issues manifest as mesh deformities during specific bone movement because the weight paint is overlapping too much on another other bone's weight paint, and thus have two bones deforming the mesh at the same time without proper falloff.

First we'll deal with the hands, select the necessary body/clothing mesh in "Weigth paint" mode (wireframe mode helps greatly for visability) then select both wrist bones named "RightHand", "LeftHand" and top thumb bones "LThumb", "RThumb" then auto weight paint or "Assign Automatic from bones" from the "Weights" menu. 

Then we'll deal with the face muscle bones, select all facial bones but be sure to deselect or NOT select eye ball bones(eye.R, eye.L), tongue bone, head and neck bones, or any other bones not on the face. Apply "Levels" from the "Weights" menu ("Levels" appears in "Tool Shelf" so be sure it's visible). In "Levels" select the "Selected Pose Bones" and change "Gain" factor to 2.0 on body mesh. All face bones should exert some RED, yellow, and green force on body mesh after "levels" adjustment but prior to adjustment it will only show yellow and green. Use a "Gain" of 10 on eye ball bones for eye mesh. Use a "Gain" of 500 for Tongue bone on tongue mesh. Some minor painting may be necessary for the tongue or eyeball mesh. Essentially bones "eye.L" and "eye.R" should exert a completely "Red" or solid force level on the eye mesh but only for their respective eye. Similarly the "tongue01" bone should exert a completely "Red" force on the tongue mesh. Note that the tongue mesh isn't added by default in Makehuman.

You should now have a completely functional rig for use in Blender. If any of you know how to fix these weight paint issues by editing *.mhw file please let me know in the comments below or send me a personal message.

565.title: Ballet dress The Swan
565.description:
Tags: female, ballet, work.
I don't know anything about ballet but this is my/our interpretation of a ballet dress and was created together with a friend who did the basic design. It is primary made for subsurf level 2. I have done extra edge loops to tighten the edges to avoid texture distortion when using modifiers.
The skirt is three vertex hard body to maintain its shape.
The chest ruffle is not displaced and if you think the normal map is to strong you can reduce the effect by painting over the area with RGB color 128 128 256 (in Blender 0.5 0.5 1.0) and low strength brush.
In MakeHuman viewport the transparent will not show in favor of the normal map. 
In Blender use the modifier "Solidify" and about 2 to 3 mm thickness and "Fill Rim" and "Only Rim" to give the fabric some thickness.

In Blender Cycles:
The diffuse texture should also be used as glossy color to make the gold pattern more visible.
The specular map is also used to adjust glossy roughness, use a "Invert"-node and connect it to the glossy shader "Roughness" to get tiny almost not noticeable glitter effect on the gold pattern.

You have to give credits to Nathan Vegdahl, Beorn Leonard, and Jonathan Williamson, based on an initial design by David Revoy.

579.description: This my first asset, but for that it's not that bad. Just a simple short pants for male characters.

580.title: heel sandals
580.description: The heel sandals are a special asset. I remodeled the feet in a specific position and created a pair of shoes with medium heels. I used the young caucasian female texture for the feet, if you want another texture, simply copy the foot of the original texture to the png-texture (you can create a new .mhmat file and a new .png in a materials folder). The complete feet of the human are deleted by using the delete vertex groups. A small gap is visible between the asset and the leg. It is build like this because a subdivision surface operation in Blender shrinks the pattern and then a bigger gap will occur. You can also reconnect the geometry in Blender (I'm doing this always). Feel free to change the material of the buckles to a glossy shader and use the same shading method for the skin of your character and this asset, so that the skin does not look different. I know, that this asset is a bit tricky ...  Edit: .mhmat file changed to material setup of "young caucasian female"

581.title: Flapper Dress 1
581.description:
20s inspired dress. Made this for a project of mine, and releasing it to the public on what happens to be the day of the Women's March against Trump. What coincidence!

Warning: mesh uses both tris and quads. The current release of MakeHuman doesn't seem to have a problem with it: it shows up correctly, and exports correctly to Blender, including rigging. It may not work for everyone's system/MH release though, so use with caution. It may export incorrectly, crash MakeHuman, fry your computer, or release the nuclear codes to a bloke called Donald. Oh, wait, that last one's already been done, nevermind ;)

Known issues: 
- Using Blender Subsurf modifier after importing from mhx2 may crash Blender or cause other issues. Doing a degenerate dissolve on the dress after import seems to fix this issue (although Blender says nothing happened). 
- As is the case with pretty much all dresses, extreme poses may look awkward.

Two additional materials are available at the materials page: http://www.makehumancommunity.org/materials.html.

Attribution not required, but always appreciated ;)

It may not work for everyone's system/MH release though, so use with caution. It may export incorrectly, crash MakeHuman, fry your computer, or release the nuclear codes to a bloke called Donald. Known issues: 
- Using Blender Subsurf modifier after importing from mhx2 may crash Blender or cause other issues. Doing a degenerate dissolve on the dress after import seems to fix this issue (although Blender says nothing happened).
- The model was made using a Caucasian adult female base mesh. Other races/ages/genders may need some very minor manual touch-up.

Two additional materials are available at the materials page: http://www.makehumancommunity.org/materials.html.

Attribution not required, but always appreciated ;)

629.title: uniform jacket (train driver)
629.description:
A typical work uniform for male characters. I modelled an historic uniform of a yugoslavian train driver used between 70s and 90s. The jacket was modelled on the base mesh with helpers. Similar uniforms are used for airline employees, post office workers, police man etc. In this case modify the texture.

You may create a complete uniform by using the jacket, cap and pants. It also works with Mindfront's oxford shoes.

Delete groups are used. The leather litsphere is only used for a visibility of the normalmap. After exporting to e.g. Blender put the color output of the texture map into the input of the glossy shader. You also may increase the factor of the normalmap to make the details more visible.

637.description: this is only a small modification to create a conductor cap instead of the train driver cap. As we all know these caps are red instead of blue (at least in most European countries). This is the former Yugoslavian version.

638.title: signal
638.description: This is a version of the signal the conductor on a platform is showing, when a train should depart. It only uses rigid vertex groups. It is the version which was in use in former Yugoslavia and still is in use in most the successor countries Croatia, Serbia, Bosnia etc. The small holes of the signal are not part of the geometry, they are simply transparent areas in the texture. So it is possible to create other signal e.g. for police by simply changing the texture.

Nevermind the politics of it. 

No matter how you feel about Trump, you might eventually need a MAGA hat for a character, like Uncle Earl, who wears his MAGA hat proudly while yelling at the neighborhood kids to get off his lawn.

653.title: greek statue nose
653.description: A target I made from shrinkwrapping the male caucasian mesh to a 3d scan of an an ancient greek bust.  downloaded the 3d scan from here, lots of cool stuff to be found:  https://www.myminifactory.com/object/portrait-of-alexander-the-great-at-the-metropolitan-museum-of-art-new-york-10461   https://www.myminifactory.com/category/scan-the-world

654.title: Anime Stylized (Enhanced)
654.description: Oscalon may have stopped working on this, but I haven't. This is a modified/fixed/enhanced version of his anime target. I primarily use it in non-100% amounts to add a degree of stylization to characters, of either sex. To that end, I restored the original shape of the eye sockets to fix the default expressions. I flattened the eyeballs somewhat (by editing the helper) to correct the "bug-out" effect at strong %s. And custom-fitted the helper geometry in general to unfreak any freaked clothes.

655.title: thinner eyelids
655.description: makes the eyelids thinner and therefore more realistic (in real life your eyelids are thin enough that the cornea deforms the eyelid as you move your eyes... not so in makehuman)

656.title: female specialsuit mask
656.description: It turns out that if you scale a skin up by exactly 158%, it lines up perfectly with the makeup masque.  This should be useful as a base for painting.

657.title: Male Chiton
657.description:
A typical ancient Greek dress, the Chiton was basically a rectangular cloth draped around the body and fastened at the shoulders. It was worn by both men and women, although in a slightly different way. The Chiton was later adapted by the Romans into their Tunica.

A diffuse texture is provided, but it is highly recommended to edit the material on import in your favourite 3d editor (Blender). Especially the fibula (fastener pin) on the left shoulder should be metallic.
This mesh uses both quads and tris, which should be OK, but it still may cause some unexpected problems.

Known issues: 
- When using a subsurf modifier in Blender, the mesh seems to disappear. Execute a Degenerate Dissolve operation to fix this.
- Some vertex bindings around the left shoulder seem a bit off. The mesh works pretty well for most poses, but for some of the more extreme ones, manual editing may be needed.

Attribution not required, though it is appreciated.

658.title: ball of pain
658.description: I messed up so now the pose is three feet off the ground, whoops

660.title: Knitted Sweater 01
660.description:
Tags: Sweater.
Unisex hand knitted sweater.
The normal map looks better at lower strength.
In Blender use the "solidify" modifier with "Thickness" about 4mm and "Fill Rim" and "Only Rim" to give it some thickness.

Preview image rendered in Blender Cycles.

661.title: Knitted Sweater 02
661.description: Tags: Sweater. Unisex hand knitted sweater. In Blender use the "solidify" modifier with "Thickness" about 4mm and "Fill Rim" and "Only Rim" to give it some thickness. Preview image rendered in Blender Cycles.

662.title: wetsuit
662.description: A wetsuit or neoprene used for swimming competitions or triathlon. It is partly based on Freehunters female bodysuit but also works for males. The delete-groups are used. The strap on the backside uses rigid groups. The leather litsphere is only used for a visibility of the normalmap in Makehuman. It is only used near the armpits ...

663.title: swim cap
663.description: A typical swim cap, which you receive when you want to do a competition. The texture contains the starting number (change it if you don't like it ...). The delete groups are used, especially to delete part of the ears. The leather litsphere is only used for a visibility of the normalmap. Throw away the hair. The goggles can be used with this cap.

664.title: Goggles
664.description: Goggles are used in swimming competitions. Part of the goggles are based on rigid groups, so that geometry will not be destroyed. Best to be used with the swim cap. It may be used with strand hair (which is not simple ...). You may change the transparent parts of the goggles in Blender to something more "glass-like".

665.title: freestyle01
665.description: A freestyle swimming pose. Normally also known as (front-)crawl.  Demo picture is made with Makehuman.

667.title: Corinthian_helmet
667.description: modelled after a true archeological find and optimised for subsurf level 2.

668.title: triathlon suit (female)
668.description: A typical one-piece triathlon suit. You wear this suit when you swim (also under the wetsuit), bike or run. The suit should be combined with a race number belt. Delete groups are used. The leather litsphere is only used for a visibility of the normalmap in Makehuman. In Blender the litsphere does not matter.

669.title: cycling shoes
669.description: A typical pair of cycling shoes, which are also used in triathlon. The sole is made on a special rigid group, so it cannot bend (like in reality). This is done because of the adaptors of the pedal system should not distort. Delete groups are used.

670.title: bicycle helmet (time trial aero helmet)
670.description: This bicycle helmet is normally used for time trial and triathlon. It is made completely on rigid groups. Please consider that using hair will create some problems. If you don't like the texts of the texture, simply change it, so that it fits your desires. In Blender you may also change the transparent parts of the eye-shield to a glass-like material.

671.title: race number belt (back)
671.description: The race number belt is a special asset to fix the race number, when you doing a race. Normally the number is worn on the back, when you ride a bicycle. For running you will need another version, because it is worn on the front. The paper with the number itself is generated on a rigid group, so it is not distorted. Nevertheless it should work for male and female characters. Change number, event and personalization on the diffuse texture to whatever you need. The litsphere makes the normal map visible. The paper should look wrinkled, like in reality. In Blender, change the safety-pins to a silver-like material.

674.title: hooded_cardigan
674.description: Purple cardigan with hood for female actors. Created as an option to go over female yoga suit.

690.title: Fangs
690.description:
this is an imperfect test that im shareing because its fun to play with
this is in clothes becasue it is just lengthend k9's and not a full set.  works best with teeth base

693.title: Foot Pose: Heels_11cm
693.description: This .bvh-file is used to pose the feet inside MH for those high heels that were modelled with this foot pose. Place this .bvh-file inside your makehuman-pose-folder. On Linux this would probably be ~/usr/share/makehuman/data/poses/

694.title: sun visor (sports visor)
694.description: From Wiki: This type of headgear was designed for use in outdoor sports (especially golf, tennis, and volleyball) where eye protection from direct sunlight is desirable, but is now often used by non-athletes at beach and other sunny outdoor events. The strap can function as a sweatband. Of course it is used for running also. It is not so simple to combine it with strand hair in Blender but even if you use it with polygon hair you normally must change geometry. A normal map is supplied. The leather litsphere is used to make the effect visible in Makehuman.

695.title: Sport-Sunglasses
695.description: This kind of sport sunglasses are used for running and biking. The glasses are completely made by using rigid groups (so there may be modifications of the head, which will not work with these glasses). In Blender you should change the transparent part of glasses to a transparent/glossy shader combination (I did it for the example picture).

696.title: race number belt (front)
696.description: The race number belt is a special asset to fix the race number, when you doing a race. Normally the number is worn at the front, when you run. For riding the bicycle you will need another version, because it is worn on the back. The paper with the number itself is generated on a rigid group, so it is not distorted. Nevertheless it should work for male and female characters. Change number, event and personalization on the diffuse texture to whatever you need. The litsphere makes the normal map visible. The paper should look wrinkled, like in reality. In Blender, change the safety-pins to a silver-like material. (the pngs for the number on the back and front are identical ... so you may also copy or link the png instead of loading them or even change the names in the mhmat file).

697.title: High Heel: Peeptoe 17.03.19
697.description:
Works best with default female. Use the pose "Heels_11cm.bvh" for this asset. It can be found in the Poses-section of this repository:
[http://www.makehumancommunity.org/content/foot_pose_heels_11cm.html].

In the picture below you can see how to combine normal- and bumpmaps in Blender (Cycles). Licensed under CC-BY-NC-SA (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Creative_Commons_license)

705.title: Vader Boots
705.description: The whole character consists of 12 items. For easy access inside MH they are tagged "Vader". Workes only flawless with gender slider to full male and everything else as default. Don't export subdivided mesh. Instead, subdivide it in Blender or elsewhere, otherwise some minor glitches may occur. There are two different capes: one already formed as cloth, the second waits for you to run a cloth-simulation on it after you posed the rest of the character (for a nicer look).

717.title: MakeHuman Medal
717.description: This is the medal I used as a finisher medal for the "triathlon episode". It is based on rigid groups using three points of a female character. So the medal keeps the geometry (hopefully).  It also worked for male characters. Sometimes you have to adjust the geometry so it is not inside some clothes. In the example picture I changed the silver and golden material to a metallic shader. Be aware that smoothing or subdivision surface algorithm does not only create a round shape it also changes the H-character in the middle of the medal a bit. I consider this as jewelry :-)

720.title: Eyes out
720.description: Makes the eyes less sunken.  Left is the original human, middle is the target applied around 50%, right is maximum eye bulging.

723.title: Foot Pose: Heels_03cm
723.description: This .bvh-file is used to pose the feet inside MH for those high heels that were modelled with this foot pose. Place this .bvh-file inside your makehuman-pose-folder. On Linux this would probably be ~/usr/share/makehuman/data/poses/

724.title: HarveyKneelingFashion1
724.description:
kneeling pose  
i manually removed frames from this bvh.  it seems to work fine.  please let me know if you have problems with it

729.title: Wedge "Pirate Djunk"
729.description:
Works best with default female. Use the pose "Heels_08cm.bvh" for this asset. It can be found in the Poses-section of this repository: 
http://www.makehumancommunity.org/content/foot_pose_heels_08cm.html +++ Licensed under CC-BY-NC-SA (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Creative_Commons_license)

730.description:
I added the 5 phases for running, these are the pushoff phase, swing phase, early, mid and late stance phase (http://www.fit4duty.co.uk/strength-training/strength-training-for-runners).
1. Phase: the pushoff

731.title: Running Swing Phase
731.description: I added the 5 phases for running, these are the pushoff phase, swing phase, early, mid and late stance phase (http://www.fit4duty.co.uk/strength-training/strength-training-for-runners). 2. Phase: Swing Phase

732.description: I added the 5 phases for running, these are the pushoff phase, swing phase, early, mid and late stance phase (http://www.fit4duty.co.uk/strength-training/strength-training-for-runners). 3. Phase: early stance phase
